The microstructural properties were evaluated using SEM, TEM, and HRTEM [73]. According to Fig. 2
                        (a), CdS-D showed a nanorod-like (NRs) with relatively uniform morphology, and the average diameter of the nanorods is about 12.5 nm. According to Fig. 2(b), ZIF-8 showed a relatively small and nanocrystal-like (NCs) morphology. As shown in Fig. 2(c), the SEM image of the CZ-2 (5.0 wt% ZIF-8) nanocomposite confirmed the incorporation of ZIF-8 NCs on the CdS-D NRs and verified by XRD, FT-IR, and Raman characterizations. The TEM images of pristine ZIF-8 NCs in Fig. 2(d) indicated an average diameter of about 40 nm. Moreover, the incorporation of ZIF-8 NCs in the CZ-2 nanocomposite was evident in the high-magnification TEM image (Fig. 2(e)). Fig. 2(f) illustrates the HRTEM image of the prepared CZ-2 nanocomposite. The crystal lattice with a spacing of 0.332 nm, corresponding to the (101) plane of CdS-D NRs, was observed in the CZ-2 nanocomposite. The SEM image for CdS NPs prepared without DETA solution in Fig. S4 showed the nanosphere-like morphology with an average diameter of 45 nm. The SEM elemental mapping analysis for CZ-2 nanocomposites (Fig. 3
                        ), CdS-D NRs (Fig. S5), and ZIF-8 (Fig. S6) were performed to evaluate the distribution of corresponding elements. The mapping pattern and EDX (Fig. S7) confirmed the presence of Cd, S, C, and N and a uniformly distributed Zn element in the CZ-2 nanocomposite. Cd2+ has a larger ionic radius (0.95) than Zn2+ (0.74), implying that ZIF-8 incorporated Zn2+ into the hexagonal structure [74]. Furthermore, ICP analysis was used to quantify the composition of the ZIF-8 modified CZ-1, CZ-2, and CZ-3 nanocomposites (
                        Table S1
                        ). There was no noticeable difference between the set ratio and the test values.
